{"version":1,"kind":"Article","sha256":"1467b1924c78a70223bd1acdfd7d28bdbc41f9db57a39b95f9a5821dfdb02303","slug":"blog.2018.rust-governance","location":"/blog/2018/rust_governance.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"I like Rust’s governance structure","tags":["python","governance","community"],"date":"2018-10-18","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"id":"chris","nameParsed":{"literal":"Chris Holdgraf","given":"Chris","family":"Holdgraf"},"name":"Chris Holdgraf","orcid":"0000-0002-2391-0678","affiliations":["affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0","affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"],"twitter":"choldgraf","github":"choldgraf","url":"https://chrisholdgraf.com"}],"github":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io","affiliations":[{"name":"2i2c","url":"https://2i2c.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0"},{"name":"Project Jupyter","url":"https://jupyter.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"}],"abbreviations":{"LF":"The Linux Foundation","JF":"The Jupyter Foundation","JEC":"Jupyter Executive Council","JFB":"The Jupyter Foundation Board","SSC":"Software Steering Council","OSPO":"Open Source Program Office"},"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"edit_url":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io/blob/main/blog/2018/rust_governance.md","thumbnail":"/build/2018-10-19-rust_logo-a56b06ad49d6080fba9b1c5abce7a686.png","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"rust_governance.md","url":"/build/rust_governance-f530fa277a8b1abf4b7ec7452f66cf78.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Recently I’ve been reading up on governance models for several large-ish open\nsource projects. This is partially because I’m involved in a bunch of\nthese projects myself, and partially because it’s fascinating to see distributed groups\nof people organizing themselves in effective (or not) ways on the internet.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"Y95etTURW4"}],"key":"tU8zfvHtpb"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Why is governance in open projects important?","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"cgTiEfvOTp"}],"identifier":"why-is-governance-in-open-projects-important","label":"Why is governance in open projects important?","html_id":"why-is-governance-in-open-projects-important","implicit":true,"key":"RyRwEyzcln"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Governance is tricky, because there is an inherent tension between:","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"ZfauFs6okF"}],"key":"D2lcT8PpUW"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Being able to make important, complex, or sensitive decisions quickly","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"S4nGEMw78F"}],"key":"dKcQra6xKp"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Being transparent and inclusive in the decision-making process","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"g5DMH9doCx"}],"key":"TOveeUrb4y"}],"key":"ZL2giVjwAr"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For most companies and organizations, the above is (sort-of) solved with a relatively\nhierarchical decision-making structure. The “Chief Executive Officer” can\ndecide high-level directions for the whole company. The team manager can\ndefine the priorities for the group.","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"key":"byT7zNOKr5"}],"key":"DLfzRyV4E2"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This generally isn’t the case in open-source, where nobody is beholden to the\nopinion of anybody else. In this case, leading and decision-making are done\nby persuading others and building coalitions. The effects of this difference often\naren’t felt in the early days of an open-source project, when the team is\nsmall, everybody knows one another, and developers often have the same perspective.\nHowever, as a project grows in its size and complexity, it becomes more important\nto create an organizational structure that recognizes, manages, and ","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"oQtUJ9H2US"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"leverages","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"iRysF8NUK3"}],"key":"xU2HJHnSpL"},{"type":"text","value":" that complexity.","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"MWcrZUTnId"}],"key":"KBo7kdMJbP"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So, this is why I like Rust’s governance model.","position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"key":"QZ7xF87RAr"}],"key":"nqlsISWRaA"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I won’t go into detail about what “Rust” is, except to say that it’s an open-source\nlanguage that has had a lot of support from the Mozilla foundation. In this case,\nI’m less interested in the specific technical pieces of that project, and want\nto focus on the people and the organizations in it.","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":40,"column":1}},"key":"dYe3AXkCKv"}],"key":"qafrDHQxGg"},{"type":"image","url":"/build/2018-10-19-rust_logo-a56b06ad49d6080fba9b1c5abce7a686.png","alt":"Rust teams","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"TAwvbbna7L","urlSource":"../../images/2018/2018-10-19-rust_logo.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Here’s the challenge that the Rust community faces:","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"j0w7mU3vZy"}],"key":"NXrNXnfUJ1"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Because Rust is an open-source language, it has a lot of technical pieces to it that\nare very diverse in the kinds of demands they have. People working on low-level kernel\nimplementation will have a different perspective from those designing libraries for\nthe language. Moreover, because this language is used by many organizations, there’s\na strong diversity in the type of user that make up the Rust community. A open-source\nlead in a company has a different incentive structure than a researcher at a university.","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"key":"qW547cIYS4"}],"key":"LJ8Pr7W97m"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This means that a single decision-making body would","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"key":"XWp42k8pBq"}],"key":"nLZfh5bD0F"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"have most of its members unable\nto make strong technical decisions about most of the sub-communities within Rust (e.g.,\na libraries and APIs person making decisions about kernel implementations).","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"h9ZE70YK1z"}],"key":"QPRCt5U1Jn"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"would be susceptible to inertia in decision-making because of the size needed to represent\nall of the Rust community with a single group of people.","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"key":"K3Khf3RYnr"}],"key":"tupAC8XRtr"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"would probably be skewed towards one set of decisions over another (since whoever was\nmost powerful within this group would set the “agenda” for the whole project)","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"key":"sgDzdOPGYm"}],"key":"DbMKOko7ru"}],"key":"fM630TXQM9"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So, here are two ways that Rust tries to address this problem:","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"PfuGHdQQKH"}],"key":"B40NYqqsRG"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":71,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Divide the governance structure into sub-teams and a “core” team.","position":{"start":{"line":69,